<TITLE> Tamim leads Tigers' fightback </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 26 (bdnews24.com)  Tamim Iqbal led a tremendous fightback with a career- best century before India hit back with two late wickets as Bangladesh ended the third day of the second Test at the Sher-e-Bangla National Stadium on 228-3, still trailing by 83 runs on Tuesday. He featured in a record 200-run stand for the second wicket with Junaid Siddique before the latter was out for 55. Three runs later, Tamim, who along the way became the fastest Bangladeshi centurion, joined Siddique in the dressing room after making 151. The left-handed Tamim, whose previous best was 134 against West Indies in 2009, brought up the milestone off 101 balls. It easily best Mushfiqur Rahim's 112-ball effort in the Chittagong Test. Mohammad Ashraful and nightwatchman Shahadat Hossain were both on two at the close of play. The second wicket pair came together after the Tigers lost Imrul Kayes, who was on pair, after lunch with scoreboard on 19. Kayes was dismissed for five, trying to check his stroke after the previous ball from Zaheer Khan unsettled him. India declared their first innings during the lunch break on 544 for eight, which gave them an overall lead of
